instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "Time synchronization across all connected devices is mandated to share a common notion of time, with a required accuracy of 100 ms to satisfy safety-critical vehicular standards that often demand stricter limits. The data exchange and computation‑offloading processes are therefore synchronized on a 100 ms temporal grid, ensuring that physical and digital states are aligned with that granularity."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin is architected following ISO 23247, with distinct entity layers: a Physical Twin Entity that hosts the underlying compute, sensors, actuators and general automotive logic (e.g., point‑cloud clustering and tracking); a Digital Twin Entity that encapsulates data management and control mechanisms; and a User Entity that contains the User Interface FE split into 3D Visualization and Control Panel components. Each entity is instantiated as one or more ROS 2 packages, each comprising one or more ROS 2 nodes that communicate via ROS 2 topics and services. The entities are deployed on separate hardware platforms, leading to a distributed orchestration that respects 100 ms clock‑synchronization across nodes. Resource management and system‑wide coordination are handled by the ROS 2 middleware, which routes messages and service calls among nodes, while ownership of functionality is determined by the physical deployment of each entity."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin System (DTS) employs an internal ROS 2 network based on DDS for communication between software components, while inter‑entity communication (e.g., between the DTS and external vehicle or user interfaces) is carried out over a Wi‑Fi radio link using the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) at the transport layer, as illustrated in Figure 2. This architecture supports real‑time, low‑latency data exchange for sensor streams and control command distribution."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is designed in accordance with ISO 23247 – Digital twin framework for manufacturing, adopting its entity‑based reference architecture.  It follows Part 2 of the standard, which defines four core entities – Observable Manufacturing Element (OME), Data Collection and Device Control Entity, Digital Twin Entity, and User Entity – each composed of Functional Entities for specific tasks such as actuator control, data transformation and user interfacing.  The implementation may use OPC Unified Architecture as an example of a Functional Entity communication protocol, ensuring interoperability with industrial automation systems."
]
